Modeling/Predicting the Growth of Bike Sharing Services in DC¶

Wenxuan Yu

Introduction:¶

Bike-sharing services have been growing in popularity, as more people are choosing biking as their means of transportation, both increasing daily exercise, and decreasing our daily carbon footprint. This tutorial will explore data from the largest and the dominant bike-sharing service in DC, Capital Bikeshare. We will gain knowledge about peoples average ride time, the number of customers, the number of bikes, and more relevant data every year from 2010 to 2017 in order to picture the growth of the largest bike-sharing service in DC.

Because of the dominant role of Capital Bikeshare in the bike-sharing market, this model would reflect the overall growth of all bike-sharing services in DC. After having our 7 years of data cleaned up, we will use tools to predict the growth rate of the market and test our prediction using later years' data.

Data Collection:¶

The data we are using comes from the Capital Bikeshare database. The same data can be found at this link, under Trip History Data: https://ride.capitalbikeshare.com/system-data We are analyzing the data from 2010 to 2017 for this part of the tutorial.

The data includes these attributes:

  • Duration Duration of trip
  • Start Date Includes start date and time
  • End Date Includes end date and time
  • Start Station Includes starting station name and number
  • End Station Includes ending station name and number
  • Bike Number Includes ID number of bike used for the trip
  • Member Type Indicates whether the user was a "registered" member (Annual Member, 30-Day Member, or Day Key Member) or a "casual" rider (Single Trip, 24-Hour Pass, 3-Day Pass, or 5-Day Pass)

The data has been processed to remove trips that are taken by staff as they service and inspect the system, trips that are taken to/from any of the test stations at the Capital Bikeshare warehouses, and any trips lasting less than 60 seconds (potentially false starts or users trying to re-dock a bike to ensure it's secure).

Data Cleaning:¶

At this part of the tutorial, we will do our best to fix-up the data. After the process, the data should be organized so that it is readable and easy to analyze. We will achieve this by manipulating our DataFrames columns and rows.

In our case of bike-sharing data, the first thing we realize is our Start date and End date columns are not DateTime objects, which is a type of object that gives us easy access to the year, month, date, and time of the data. We will transform the two columns with pandas.to_datetime function.

After that, to identify which year is each row representing, we will extract the year from "Start date" column for every row, and create a new column showing us the year. This will also make actions like grouping data by year easier later. Finally, we will create new columns Day, "Hour", and Month to indicate the datas day of week, hour, and month. All these extra data will come in handy later when we try to analyze what day of the week people use bike-sharing services the most, for example, easier. We can always add more columns if needed later.

More information about DateTime can be found here: https://docs.python.org/3/library/datetime.html

More information about pandas.to_datetime can be found here: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.to_datetime.html

In [6]:
# We are converting 'Start date' and 'End date' columns to pandas DateTime objects. This way we can extract year, month, day, and time easily.
data_cp['Start date'] = pd.to_datetime(data_cp['Start date'])
data_cp['End date'] = pd.to_datetime(data_cp['End date'])
# Now we are adding a column called 'Year' to our DataFrame, so we can group our data by year easily.
data_cp['Year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data_cp['Start date']).year
# Adding the "Day" column indicating day-of-week
data_cp['Day'] = data['Start date'].dt.day_name()
# Adding the "Hour" column indicating hour of the day
data_cp['Hour'] = data['Start date'].dt.hour
# Adding the "Month" column indicating month
data_cp['Month'] = data['Start date'].dt.month

Checking Missing Data

After adding the columns we need, we will check if there are any missing data (e.g. NaN). If NaN exist for any columns, we would drop them in our case, because it makes that row of data useless. However, we are lucky that there is no NaN value presented!

Data Analysis:¶

In this part of the tutorial, we aim to gain comprehensive knowledge of our data, using tools like different plots/graphs to visualize it.

We will be visualizing:

  • The total number of bike-sharing between 2010 - 2017
  • The number of registered members between 2010 - 2017
  • Where are the top used stations/locations located? 2010 - 2017
  • The total number of bikes shared on each day of the week
  • The total number of bikes shared in each hour of the day
  • The total number of bikes shared in each month of the year

Tools:

  • pandas.DataFrame.groupby() function, which groups the data in a data frame with given parameters, such as column names. Heavily used when extracting year, month, week, and day data. More information can be found here: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.groupby.html
  • ax.plot() function, which returns a line plot of given independent and dependent variables. More information can be found here: https://matplotlib.org/3.5.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.plot.html
  • ax.bar() function, which returns a bar graph with given categories and corresponding data. More information here: https://matplotlib.org/3.5.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.bar.html
  • folium library, which is a python library that provides easy means to create an interactive map. More information can be found here: https://towardsdatascience.com/creating-a-simple-map-with-folium-and-python-4c083abfff94

Predicting the Growth of The Bike Sharing Service in DC¶

In this part of the tutorial, we will use linear and non-linear models to predict the growth rate of this bike-sharing service in DC. We will test out models with 2018, 2019, and 2020 data!

Tools:

  • ax.scatter() function, which returns a scatter plot with given dependent and independent variables. We use a scatter plot so it is easy to fit a linear/non-linear regression. More information can be found here:https://matplotlib.org/3.5.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.scatter.html More info on linear regression in python can be found here: https://realpython.com/linear-regression-in-python/
  • sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression function is an easy-to-use Python library that provides linear regression models. More information can be found here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression.html
  • This is an example code on a simple linear regression model, check it out if you are interested! https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/linear_model/plot_ols.html
  • sklearn.preprocessing.PolynomialFeatures. This is for our high-degrees, non-linear models. Check more information out here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.preprocessing.PolynomialFeatures.html

First lets import our data for 2018, 2019, and 2020. We will follow the same steps as at the beginning of the tutorial.

In [61]:
# For linear modle
from sklearn import linear_model

# fitting the linear regression
lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()

# year_2d is just the years but in 2d array form, e.g. [[2010],[2011],[2012],...,[2017]]
# the reason for this is that lm.fit, which gives us back a linear regression, can only take
# 2d array as a parameter!
year_2d = [ [year] for year in year_arr ]
# Same idea for each year's data, it has to be in a 2d array
total_2d = [ [data] for data in total_each_year ]

The line visually looks good, but we can statistically see how well the line fits the data by looking at its R^2 value. When the R^2 value is 1 that means our linear line fits the data perfectly well (e.g. every point is on the line), and when R^2 value is 0 that means the model is nonsense and there is nothing predictive about the model :( So let's see our R^2!

In [65]:
print(lm.score(year_2d,total_2d))

0.9134884865740657

0.91 is really good! Imagine getting a 91 in any CS class, right? Usually, its an A! And so is our model! Let's look at our model's prediction on 2018-2020 compare to the actual number!

      (3542684, 3398417, 537400, (predicted_2018-3542684)/3542684*100, (predicted_2019-3398417)/3398417*100, (predicted_2020-537400)/537400*100))

As we can see, the actual data is that in 2018 there is 3542684 bike shares, in 2019 3398417, and in 2020 537400. Our linear model predicted 2018 by 27.73 percent off, 2019 by 47.12 percent off, and 2020 by 918.63 percent off.

What happened?

Lets talk about 2020 first. As we can see there is significantly less data for the year 2020 compared to 2018 and 2019. Therefore it is clear that something happened in the year 2020 (we all know it's COVID), and that the amount of data in the year 2020, does not apply to our linear model, or even any predictive model we make.

As for the years 2018 and 2019, we will next try using nonlinear models to see if we can get the prediction closer to reality.

# Plotting!

degree2_poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
degree2_years = degree2_poly.fit_transform(year_2d)
lm.fit(degree2_years, total_2d)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(13,13))

ax.scatter(year_arr, total_each_year)

      % (lm.score(degree2_years,total_2d)))

Our R^2 score for degree 2 polynomial model is 0.9871

This time degree 2 polynomial model gives us an even better R^2 score of 0.9871! This time we get a straight-up A+ for our model ;). Lets again see how it predicts the years 2018 and 2019!

The actual data is that in 2018 there is 3542684 bike shares, and in 2019 3398417. Our degree 2 poly model predicted 2018 by 0.78 percent off, and 2019 by 2.42 percent off.

This is really, really good! Our degree 2 polynomial model predicts the year 2018 and 2019 almost perfectly! And the reason for this might be that the growth rate of the number of people using the bike-sharing service is decreasing, therefore our growth model is an increasing line with a decreasing rate (e.g. a growing, concaving down graph).

Now lets see what the line look like when we add in the year 2018 and 2019!
